Scraping game scores.

Scraping all the scores up until the end of January of 2018. No comments, simply dig into this code upon your desire. We’ve covered very similar examples with college football data.

library(rvest)  # Should be installed along with 'xml2'
## Loading required package: xml2
months <- c("october","november","december","january")
all_games <- NULL

for (month_name in months){
  url_link <- paste('https://www.basketball-reference.com/leagues/NBA_2018_games-', 
                    month_name,
                    '.html',
                    sep="")

  # Read the HTML webpage for that link into an R object
  url <- read_html(url_link)
  url

  # Find a 'table' on that HTML page
  table_one <- xml_find_all(url, "//table") 
  # Obtain the actual contents of the table, wrapped into a data frame
  table_one <- html_table(table_one)
  length(table_one)

  all_games <- rbind(all_games,table_one[[1]])
}

Scraping team performance stats.

Here we’ll repeat the code we used to scrape data for NBA team clustering (see the respective code), with only exception being - we’ll obtain data until Jan 31st (to include a full month of January), rather that Jan 18th.

url_link <- 'https://www.basketball-reference.com/friv/standings.fcgi?month=1&day=31&year=2018&lg_id=NBA'

# Read the HTML webpage for that link into an R object
url <- read_html(url_link)
url
## {xml_document}
## <html data-version="klecko-" data-root="/home/bbr/www" itemscope="" itemtype="https://schema.org/WebSite" lang="en" class="no-js">
## [1] <head>\n<meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset= ...
## [2] <body class="bbr">\n\n<div id="wrap">\n  <div id="header" role="bann ...
# Define the function to extract the "commented out" tables.

find_extra_table <- function(url_link){
  # Additional tables are within the comment tags -  between "<!--"  and  "-->"
  # Which is why your xpath is missing them.
  
  # Find all the commented nodes. 
  # xml_find_all looks in-between the <> of the object resulting from read_html().
  alt_tables <- xml_find_all(read_html(url_link),"//comment()")
  
  #Among commented nodes, find those containing '<table' reg. expression 
  #raw_parts <- as.character(alt_tables[grep("\\</?table", as.character(alt_tables))])
  raw_parts <- as.character(alt_tables[grep("<table", as.character(alt_tables))])
  
  # Remove the comment begin ("<!--") and end ("-->") tags
  strip_html <- stringi::stri_replace_all_regex(raw_parts, c("<\\!--","-->"),c("",""),
                                                vectorize_all = FALSE)
  
  # Read all the tables that used to be commented before.
  alt_tables <- lapply(grep("<table", strip_html, value = TRUE), function(i){
    rvest::html_table(xml_find_all(read_html(i), "//table"))[[1]]
  })
  
  return(alt_tables)
}

Actual Modeling.

Now that we’ve got:

  • the characteristics (performance stats) of each team, kept in \(all\_stats\) object,
  • the scores for all NBA 2017/18 season games played until January 31st, kept in \(all\_games\)

we need to somehow use the characteristics of teams \(A\) & \(B\) as predictors for the eventual score of a game between \(A\) & \(B\). We will be using the completed games to train and test our model’s performance.

Getting data into needed format.

Unfortunately, we’re not done getting data into needed format. We have to perform extra merging to actually put it into classic \(observations \ \times variables\) format. Below code achieves that, and don’t ask me how exactly it does it (the way to get there was pretty messy).

colnames(all_games)
## [1] "Visitor/Neutral" "PTS"             "Home/Neutral"    "PTS.1"
full_data <-  merge(all_games, all_stats, by.x=c("Visitor/Neutral"), by.y=c("Team"))
p <- dim(full_data)[2]-4
full_data <- merge(full_data, all_stats, by.x=c("Home/Neutral"), by.y=c("Team"))

The \(PTS.1\) value corresponds to the score differential for the home team in that game. E.g. \(-10\) in the first row means that home team lost by \(10\) points (there’s plenty of home team losing in first 6 observations, as those are Atlanta Hawks home games …).

The rest of stats are treated similarly:

  • \(FGA.x.y\) corresponds to differential in average FG attempts per game for the home team (\(\text{FGA for home team}\) - \(\text{FGA for away team}\)),
  • \(FG\%x.y\) is the difference in FG% for the home team (\(\text{FG% for home team}\) - \(\text{FG% for away team}\))
  • …
  • \(FG\%y.y\) is the difference in FG% allowed for the home team (\(\text{FG% allowed by home team}\) - \(\text{FG% allowed by away team}\))

Finally… modeling.

Now we can use the stat differentials between teams \(A\) and \(B\) in order to predict the score differential of a game between \(A\) and \(B\)! We will refer to a classical multiple linear model, which can be fit via \(lm()\) function:

lm.obj <- lm(PTS.1 ~ ., data=diff_data)
summary(lm.obj)

Let’s break down the significant variables:

  • 3PT attempt differential (\(3PA.x.y\)) appears important, with a positive influence on a score differential (teams taking more threes per game than their opponents have a higher chance to win), which is… curious
  • Positive differential in turnovers committed (\(TOV.x.y\)) has a significant negative impact on the score differential (teams committing more turnovers per game than their opponent have a lower chance to win), which is pretty clear.
  • Positive differential in turnovers forced (\(TOV.y.y\)) has a significant positive impact on the score differential (teams forcing more turnovers per game than their opponent have a higher chance to win), which is also clear.
  • How about the intercept term? This is a pretty rare occasion where it actually means something really important - advantage of a home team. It is equal to an average across all games by which the home team outscores the visitor. Here it is significantly higher than \(0\) and shows an advantage of 2.2 points per home team on average. intercept term is here described what’s the average score differential for a home team. So it says that, on average, home teams beat opponents by 2.2 points.

Now, all these interpretations are great, but one has to be worried about an overflow of seemingly unimportant predictors in the model (ones with high \(p\)-values). There a couple of ways we can go about getting rid of irrelevant variables.

Variance Inflation Factor.

Issue of multi-collinearity arises when certain predictors can be represented as linear combinations of other predictors, which leads to instability of parameter estimation in linear models. Multicollinearity reduces a model’s legitimacy and predictive power.

Sometimes multi-collinearity among predictors is pretty obvious, such as \(FGA = 3PA + 2PA\), but we did take care of those by hand in the earlier stages.

But at times the multi-collinearity is sneakier and isn’t easy to spot by hand. This is where Variance Inflation Factor (VIF) comes in handy. Variance inflation factors of a predictor allows a quick measure of how much this predictor is increasing (inflating) the standard errors (hence, variance) of regression estimates in our linear model.

VIF of each predictor can be calculated via \(vif()\) function of \(car\) library.

library(car)
## Loading required package: carData
vif(lm.obj)
##   FGA.x.y `FG%.x.y` `3PA.x.y` `3P%.x.y`   ORB.x.y   TRB.x.y   AST.x.y 
##  9.268148 22.645327  2.001622  4.029451 47.052555 98.565065  5.872309 
##     BLK.y   TOV.x.y      PF.y   FGA.y.y `FG%.y.y` `3PA.y.y` `3P%.y.y` 
##  7.343272  6.983332  3.614322 61.528035 25.761260  4.459482  7.661466 
##   ORB.y.y   TRB.y.y   AST.y.y   TOV.y.y 
## 21.743406 17.436275  9.059465  3.391909

“Good” The values of VIF between \(1\) and \(10\) are considered good, meaning that this predictor is not subject to multi-collinearity.

But once you get VIF > \(10\), those variables are suspect and probably need to be removed. Here we see TRB.x.y (difference in total rebounds by the team) yielding a 98.56 VIF => let’s get rid of it.

vif(lm(PTS.1 ~ .-TRB.x.y, data=diff_data))
##   FGA.x.y `FG%.x.y` `3PA.x.y` `3P%.x.y`   ORB.x.y   AST.x.y     BLK.y 
##  9.127315 22.213948  1.897296  3.990388 17.010910  5.786667  7.264003 
##   TOV.x.y      PF.y   FGA.y.y `FG%.y.y` `3PA.y.y` `3P%.y.y`   ORB.y.y 
##  6.977551  3.421531 15.726058 10.394771  4.429147  7.344776  7.184701 
##   TRB.y.y   AST.y.y   TOV.y.y 
## 17.435996  8.550535  3.317310

One sees how most VIFs got automatically reduced once this suspect variable got eliminated, pointing to the fact that it probably had heavy collinearities with multiple predictors. Now let’s keep eliminating the predictors producing largest VIF values that end up above \(10\).

vif(lm(PTS.1 ~ .-TRB.x.y-`FG%.x.y`, data=diff_data))

Now that all the remaining predictors end up in the healthy VIF range, we re-fit our linear model for that reduced set of predictors.

lm.obj <- lm(PTS.1 ~ .-TRB.x.y-`FG%.x.y`-FGA.y.y, data=diff_data)
summary(lm.obj)

Stepwise model selection.

To further reduce the model we can refer to stepwise model selection, where we * Drop the least significant variables one at a time, * until we reach a model containing solely important variables.

Function \(step()\) allows us to do this in \(R\) (no further details provided, as I did spend a good amount of time explaining it in class):

lm.obj.step <- step(lm.obj, trace=F)
summary(lm.obj.step)

Evaluating Predictive Performance.

Now, for the reduced model, let’s get the predicted score differentials for each game, and look at the first few.

pred.diff <- predict(lm.obj.step)
head(pred.diff)
##          1          2          3          4          5          6 
## -2.6057414 -1.1003282  0.2826407 -0.2595163  2.1416684 -5.5585858

Now let’s compare those against true point differentials observed for those games:

true.diff <- diff_data$PTS.1

# Mean Absolute Error (MAE)
mean(abs((pred.diff - true.diff)))
## [1] 9.617436

Average deviation of the predicted point differential from the true one is \(9.61\). How about we check up some pairings of actual and predicted point differential values?

# In order to look at first few games in particular:
pred.matrix <- cbind(True=true.diff,
                     Predicted=pred.diff)

To grasp the overall distribution of residuals for our prediction, we go:

plot(lm.obj.step, which=1)

No particular pattern, centered around 0, mostly ranging from \(-40\) to \(40\).

So we got an idea about the average prediction error. How about predicting the sign of the point differential correctly (which automatically determines whether we predict the winning team correctly)?

mean(predict(lm.obj.step)*true.diff >= 0)
## [1] 0.6552632

Roughly \(65\%\) of correct sign identifications, hence correct predictions of winner/loser.

\(65\%\) might be underwhelming, but it will seem even worse once I say that it is an optimistic error estimate. We calculated it using the model’s performance on the same data that the model was trained on. It is a no-no when trying to develop a generalizable model, meaning a model that will work on the new data.

Model Validation: Training/Testing subset.

To potentially describe how our linear model would work on new data, we refer to sub-dividing our data set into

  • Training subset (data used to train the model), and
  • Testing (holdout) subset (data used to validate the model performance).

To do this, we randomly sample \(80\%\) of indices for observations to be used as training data, while saving the remaining \(20\%\) for hold-out testing of our fitted modeL

set.seed(1)
n <- nrow(diff_data)
train <- sample(n,0.8*n)
test <- c(1:n)[-train]

lm.obj <- lm(PTS.1 ~ ., data=diff_data,
             subset = train)

We will fit our reduced model only to the observations from training set now:

# Just to remind ourselves the names of variables included into our reduced model
# One can simply copy-paste the 'formula' part of the output into the 
# subsequent lm() call to fit the model to training data

lm.obj.step
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = PTS.1 ~ `3PA.x.y` + BLK.y + TOV.x.y + PF.y + `3P%.y.y` + 
##     ORB.y.y + TRB.y.y, data = diff_data)
## 
## Coefficients:
## (Intercept)    `3PA.x.y`        BLK.y      TOV.x.y         PF.y  
##      2.2292       0.5125       1.7401      -1.3726      -0.5445  
##   `3P%.y.y`      ORB.y.y      TRB.y.y  
##   -115.2842       1.1051      -1.3425
lm.obj.train <- lm(PTS.1 ~ `3PA.x.y` + BLK.y + TOV.x.y + PF.y + `3P%.y.y` + ORB.y.y + TRB.y.y, 
                   data=diff_data,
                   subset=train)

Next, we need to calculate the performance metrics - mean absolute error and sign prediction error - on the testing (held-out) data.

test.true <- diff_data[test,'PTS.1']
test.predict <- predict(lm.obj.train,
                        newdata = diff_data[test,-1])

## Mean Absolute Error (MAE) rate on test data.
mean(abs(test.true - test.predict))
## [1] 10.33501
## Proportion of times we predicted the sign correctly 
# (positive/negative point differential)
mean(test.true*test.predict>0)
## [1] 0.6381579

Now we get a \(9.84\) mean absolute error and \(63.1\%\) of correct sign predictions for test data, both worse than what we got when fitting the full model and calculating its training error (which was optimistic).

But if you were to re-run the post-\(set.seed()\) code over and over again, you will see a different result every time, all due to a different subdivision into training and test data (the \(sample()\) function would provide a different set of indices each time).

Cross-Validation.

In order to avoid this variability of error estimates, cross-validation comes in handy. \(K\)-fold cross-validation consists of

  • Breaking the data set into \(K\) equally-sized subsets.
  • Proceeding to use each of those \(K\) subsets as test subset, while using remaining \(K-1\) to train the model.
  • Obtain \(K\) estimates of test set error and average them for a final test error estimate.

All this can be performed via \(cv.glm()\) function that comes with \(boot\) library. One caveat - we will need to re-run our full linear model fit, now using a \(glm()\) function rather than \(lm()\). The only reason for this - \(lm()\) doesn’t support the automated cross validation function, while \(glm()\) does.

The interface of \(glm()\) and \(lm()\) for the purpose of fitting a classic linear model is identical, only \(summary()\) outline differs a bit:

glm.obj <- glm(PTS.1 ~ `3PA.x.y` + BLK.y + TOV.x.y + PF.y + `3P%.y.y` + ORB.y.y + TRB.y.y,
               data=diff_data)
summary(glm.obj)
##

Now, let’s load the \(boot\) library and run the cross-validation via \(cv.glm()\) applied to our fitted model (kept in object \(glm.obj\)):

library(boot)
## 
## Attaching package: 'boot'
## The following object is masked from 'package:car':
## 
##     logit
set.seed(1)

cv.obj <- cv.glm(data=diff_data, 
                 glm.obj, 
                 K=10,
                 cost = function(x,y) mean(x*y>0))

cv.obj$delta
## [1] 0.6473684 0.6459211

The \(cost\) argument specifies the function of \(true\) (\(\equiv x\)) and \(predicted\) (\(equiv y\)) values of point differentials for our model. What we want is the average of times the signs of predicted point differentials (\(y\)) corresponded to the actual ones (\(x\)), which is captured via expression \(mean(x*y > 0)\).

The \(K=10\)-fold cross-validation shows a test error of 64% for our model, a bit worse than the training error, which is expected but isn’t that bad as far as ability of our model to generalize to new data is concerned.
